name: Kay Ashaolu
title: Continuing Lecturer
headline: I help junior software engineers learn how to design systems end to end in the first year of their career
description: Passionate about accelerating early-career growth, I blend my experience as a software engineer, manager, and university lecturer in web architecture to empower junior engineers. I firmly believe that with the right guidance, they can contribute to designing complex systems typically considered beyond their expertise. Leveraging my industry and academic experience, I focus on teaching tried-and-true front-end and back-end components and how they can be connected to build complex systems. My mission is to bridge the knowledge gap by providing resources that help junior engineers master system design.

These ‚Äúmodel services‚Äù are a system to export mongo‚Äôs replication logs to kafka and aggregate the updates in a stateful service to cache joins in redis. 

Built a read-only key-value store to deliver offline data to our online services called hfile service. Developed open-source replacement written in go called quiver. Rewriting in go lowered per process overhead enough to enable a single process per hfile. Wrote orchestration tool to automatically verify and deploy new data from our HDFS cluster. 

Built delta-service to combine offline data with mongodb. Quiver serves the majority of the data cheaply while mongodb stores write on a short TTL. Engineers use a reimplementation of our ORM rogue. 

Team lead on an experimental key-value store called ‚ÄúKyiv‚Äù to replace our model services. Kyiv is a scala service that stored data in rocksdb. It also uses Kafka as a distributed write log, and aurora/mesos to provide scheduling. Gobblin was used to create rollups from kafka to allow kyiv instances to bootstrap. 
Rewrote image resizer service to lower machine costs. After 5 years of running in production, migrated to imgix to reduce overall cost and remove technical debt. 

Lead initiatives to raise standards around code review, launches, infrastructure changes, and post-mortems. Run a weekly meeting to facilitate cross-team discussion of large code or architectural changes. Member of our on-call rotation. Responsible for responding to alerts and resolving incidents. 

Provide direct mentorship to junior team members. Hold office hours to provide guidance on infrastructure to support new products.

name: Dawn Lambeth
title: Developer Advocate
headline: Software Eng and Dev Advocate at Stripe
description:
I'm a software developer with over a decade of experience on a variety of projects and in several languages.  I've worked on enterprise level solutions as well as custom websites for small business.  I enjoy explaining complex technical systems in non technical terms, getting up to speed quickly with new languages and systems, and digging deep to find that elusive bug. 

I've been at Stripe since 2015 where I spent most of my time helping our largest customers and strategic partners build their integrations.  These days I'm excited to use that experience as a developer advocate, helping developers get started on Stripe. 

I'm also a jazz and swing musician, you can find out more about my music at http://www.dawnlambeth.com

description:
Engineering Manager for the Pinterest Homefeed Candidate Generation team.  Our mission is to find the most personalized, relevant pins for your Pinterest Homefeed.  We do this all on-demand and in realtime, fetching from a corpus of billions of pins, while using different recommendation algorithms.

Previously, I was the backend lead for Watch Tab and worked on different areas related to recommendations on Homefeed at Pinterest, covering the entire stack from candidate generation to serving to new product features.  I've also worked on local search and autocomplete for maps at Apple.  I have experience in recommendations, machine learning, large scale data processing, and distributed systems.

name: Alex Zylman
title: Senior Staff Engineer
headline: Senior Staff Engineer at Uber
description:
I'm an experienced technical leader. I focus on designing and building scalable, fault-tolerant systems that anticipate the needs of the business.

Currently I'm reporting to the head of commerce, leading efforts across 15+ teams in 5+ countries to unify disparate systems into a cohesive "Commerce Platform" to serve complex business requirements across Uber's growing number of product lines.

Previously, I managed 1/3rd of Clever's engineering team, focusing primarily on infrastructure where I built out the Docker-based deployment and observability tooling on AWS. 

Even more previously, I built out Clever's data pipeline and task queue system that ingested roster data, profiled and improved latency in critical services, developed an iOS app that jump-started our growth, and continually kept in mind the needs of our customers.

Specialties: Building things

name: Andrew Archer
title: Senior Software Engineer
headline: Senior Software Engineer at Airbnb
description:
I love to see people use the things we build.

Whether that's Slack's "Custom Status" feature or the external account linking flow at Wealthfront -- I've felt a profound sense of accomplishment when people engage with things I've created.

Before working as a Frontend Engineer at Slack and Wealthfront, I spent eight years at Google as at TPM and in Operations working closely with product and engineering teams.

In 2014, I took a sabbatical from Google to complete Dev Bootcamp and convert my hobbyist's interest in software development into my vocation. I enjoyed researching new technologies, writing clean code, pairing with peers, and performing behavior- and test-driven development.

My mission now is to continue learning, code every day with others, and build software that people love.

name: Anand Doshi
title: Lead Design Technologist
headline: Design Technologist at Square
description:
Hello! 

I am Anand, a product designer with extensive software engineering experience. I would describe myself as a generalist: I am curious about everything, creative, and rigorous. I enjoy working with others, and appreciate the feeling of being considered dependable.

For 5 years, I worked as a CTO / Full-stack Engineer at a startup in Mumbai, where I wore many hats, and built an open-source business application as part of a small team. I went to grad school to study UX Design, and worked on a wide variety of projects involving UX research, digital and tangible interactions, and graphic design.

At the moment, I live in Berkeley and work at Square / Block Inc. as a Sr. Design Technologist.

name: Freeland Abbott
title: Technical Lead
headline: Tech Lead & Software Engineer at Square
description:
Please don't talk to me about relocation.  I live in Boulder, CO; my wife's job is here, and I'm not about to mess her up for your once-in-a-lifetime opportunity in San Francisco or New York or wherever.  For that matter, I'm pretty happy as I am... but I'm willing to talk about other options near Boulder.  Not so much about things elsewhere.

That out of the way, I'm a senior software engineer, full-stack including JavaScript and Android.  I've held management and leadership jobs, and might interested in returning to that with a local-office environment (which I haven't had in a while, which is why I didn't try to keep that role).  I code in Kotlin, Java, Go, C/C++, Python, Javascript, and other languages.  I'm familiar with many of Google's cloud products, and at least aware of the analogous AWS offerings.  I also know Android, and I'm open to learning iOS but haven't yet had to.

Outside of work, I juggle, I do woodworking (minor cabinetry and home improvement, mostly), and these days I've swapped out playing flute and ultimate for keeping track of teen children and too dang many pets.

‚Ä¢ Contributed to the servicing platform that backs a variety of consumer and business loan products. Business multi-loan support, forbearance and loan hold rate relief.
---

My work on Consumer Financing now focuses on growth. I develop features across acquisition, risk/underwriting, and servicing.

‚Ä¢ Lead for multi-loan project. Consumer financing previously limited each person to one active loan at a given time. Defined new risk rules, updated finance and customer identity models, and changed application flow logic to support multi-loan. Collaborated with product, data science, design, and customer operations. Organized work amongst four engineers.

name: Caitlin Colgrove
title: Co-Founder and CTO
headline: Co-Founder and CTO at Hex
description:
What I love most about being a software engineer is building products that combine the best parts of technological solutions with human expertise to solve problems in the real world. I've built mobile search interfaces for police officers, providing instant access to life-saving information; document analysis and triage applications for lawyers, improving the accuracy and efficiency of the e-discovery process by orders of magnitude; and collaborative, high-scale data analysis tools for the engineers who diagnose and fix critical issues with in-service aircraft.

Though I've spent most of my development time building modern web interfaces, I've also learned that delivering an excellent product requires attention across the entire stack, from the product vision and user experience down to the nuts and bolts of the backend services. I've never been afraid to move up and down the stack to address whatever the most pressing technical challenge is at the time.

Technology is important, but all software teams are also made up of people, which is why I invest a lot of my time in areas like hiring and people growth. I discovered a love of teaching while in college and have continued that pursuit in industry, first through mentorship and later as a people manager for the engineering team I lead. As manager, I've grown people into senior engineers and leads of their own teams ‚Äì it's been one of the most rewarding aspects of my job.
